Metcash launches a bottom-up campaign to fight Aldi 's onslaught
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from Aldi's onslaught in South Australia and Western Australia.
A bottom-up food wholesaler has launched a campaign to protect IGA's market share in South Australia and Western Australia in light of Aldi's upcoming $700 million investment.
As Aldi prepares to open two wholesale warehouses and the first of 120 stores in South and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening relationships with local food suppliers and promoting the IGA brand through marketing in leading media and social media and at events such as the Adelaide Show.
IGA retailers and suppliers are joining the campaign, such as Dunsborough-based ice cream manufacturer Simmo's, which offers tastings in IGA stores, and shopkeepers who sell discounted tickets to regular customers for South Australian Football League matches.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details of its defense strategy on September 29 - the day the wholesale supplier of food, liquor and consumer goods will hold its annual Investor Strategy Day.
There is a lot at stake, as IGA-branded stores in South Australia and Western Australia account for almost 30% of all Metcash stores and show higher profitability than the Metcash IGA network in the eastern states.
Shoppers in South and Western Australia are known to be proponents of the usual routes, so the market here is more favourable to IGA retailers than in the states of New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - over 30 per cent in South Australia and 24 per cent in WA compared to about 14 per cent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will take 5 percent of the food market in these two states within 12 months of opening its first stores, taking sales from all the players present, but mostly from independent retailers.
In a report released this week, Tom Kirath, an analyst at Morgan Stanley, estimates that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales per year, and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
The forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in South Africa and 30 in WA next year, achieving sales of $500 million and $600 million in these markets respectively.
The loss of revenue and food sales at a high level of fixed costs could cost Metcash about 13 million in pre-tax and interest income, Mr. Kirat estimates.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly because of Aldi and Coles, and that's despite a recent study by Morgan Survey finding that IGA has the most loyal customers.
Morgan Stanley estimates that Metcash's food sales will fall 3.8 percent in 2016, 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, reducing the company's market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglas, founder of Magellan Financial Group, remarked to those attending a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash "could very likely disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to comment publicly on Mr. Douglas's comments.
But it's believed that a board member of Metcash contacted Mr. Douglas last week.
IGA's market share has declined from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and Metcash's revenue from its food business, which the company supplies to approximately 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen 43 percent compared to 2012 due to operational deliverables and pressure on sales and profitability.
However, the company is not giving up, spending more than $150 million annually to match retail prices at Coles and Woolworths at 1,000 positions a week and helping IGA retailers to redesign their retail locations, as well as offering a rapidly expanding range of fresh produce and a wider selection of branded food products.
Metcash CEO Ian Morris says price equalization and retail space redesigns are gaining momentum, and he hopes the company will see net profit increase in 2017, the first in four years.
