Euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, welcome to Euronews!
Wangelis Meimarakis: Thank you for the invitation.
Euronews: Nine months ago your party suffered a crushing defeat, losing to the SYRIZA coalition, but now, according to polls, New Democracy is on par with it in popularity.
What's changed in that time?
Vangelis Meimarakis: Greece has changed, and so have we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot in January of last year.
Nine months ago, Greece had a budget surplus and a growth outlook.
Now the country is again in budget deficit and high unemployment.
The investors left because Mr. Tsipras kicked them out.
Over the last nine months, the Greeks have had a chance to assess the situation the country was in in January, and Mr. Tsipras' false promises.
And now they can easily compare what they've been promised with what's actually happened.
Everyday life has become noticeably worse than in January, when the situation improved, and this was true for most Greek citizens.
Euronews: But you say that if you win the elections you will seek alliances with other parties, including SYRIZA.
Wangelis Meimarakis: The point is, as we've learned over the last few years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
And it is no coincidence that in all the other countries where rescue programs were or are still in operation, political forces and all the ruling parties came together to implement the program they had agreed upon, without giving up their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that at this stage only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
Euronews: Your party voted in favour of the agreement between Mr Tsipras and the country's creditors.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you keep that agreement, or try to change it, at least in part?
Wangelis Meimarakis: We actually voted for Greece to go on the European path, because we have a good idea of the devastating consequences of leaving the EU.
Europe is helping us now by subsidizing our farmers for their produce, we have solidarity funds, we have the Juncker package and we have help in the banking sector.
All this would be lost if there were no treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures are the result of Mr. Tsipras' negotiating style.
I know Europe doesn't want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
So if Europe sees that the new Greek government, within its first year in power, wants to bring order, acts rationally and shows that the country has a strong political will to implement the bailout programme, then I am sure that all the commitments that have been made that cannot be fulfilled because of the recession that is leading to it can be renegotiated, but only after a certain period of time.
It would be a mistake to think that we can return to negotiations with our creditors within the first year of the new agreement, because they expect the agreement to be fully implemented.
If we want to regain their trust, we must continue the privatisation, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed upon, while continuing to take advantage of EU funding and the great investment opportunities that we must unlock for better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, the Tsipras government did not present any serious arguments on many key policy issues during the negotiations, which we have found out by discussing these issues with our European colleagues.
I can give you an example of what farmers' incomes are.
