Does David Cameron know anything else about the Lorax?
One thing every parent learns very quickly is that if your child likes a book, it will be some time before you know it almost by heart.
I guess, unless you're David Cameron.
When asked by a representative of a holiday company about his favourite children's book, the prime minister chose "The Lorax", an ecologically-minded tale written by Dr. Seuss in 1971.
It was a difficult choice, Cameron wrote in a commentary posted on the SuperCamps website, and continues: "This is a fun, moving, unusual story with a powerful message that I love to read to my children because it always finds some image or message that we miss".
And it would be fine, except for the last paragraph, where Cameron is supposed to retell the book's content, but actually tells the story of the 2012 film of the same name, with new characters and details added to diversify the fairly short original narrative.
"In the walled city of Vsemnuzhville, where there was no greenery and even the air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey, the girl of his dreams, by fulfilling her wish to see a real tree", reads the text's description of the love story of an unknown Dr. Sue (real name Theodore Sue Geisel), who died in 1991.
If that doesn't sound suspicious enough, Cameron's text reads almost like a summary of the plot of the film The Lorax, as posted on the Internet Movie Database: "In the walled city of Vsemnuzhville, where everything was artificial and even the air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey, the girl of his dreams".
It seems unlikely that Cameron, an admittedly active parent, would be so unfamiliar with the contents of the book in which the unnamed boy learns about the environmental destruction of greedy tree-cutter and "sweetheart" weaver Nahodkins, despite the protests of Lorax (whose name is inserted in the book's title) - a funny, mustachioed creature who "speaks for the trees".
It's likely that this simple PR task was assigned to a performer who had never read a book about the Lorax to a child 20 times in a row.
A Downing Street spokeswoman said the text was allegedly obtained from Cameron's office in the constituency.
SuperCamps confirmed that the text was obtained from Cameron's headquarters, but no further comment was forthcoming.
