Experts criticize the e-cigarette review by Public Health England
The government-funded agency's claims that e-cigarettes are 95 percent less harmful than smoking were made at a meeting of 12 people, some of whom are associated with the tobacco industry, the researchers said.
Experts published in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) in collaboration with the Lancet have criticized the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on e-cigarettes.
PHE published a landmark report last month, calling it a "comprehensive review of the evidence".
But some researchers questioned the veracity of the data and pointed to the connection of some experts to the tobacco industry.
An editorial in the Lancet medical journal last month criticized the "extremely shaky argument" on which PHE based its main conclusion.
In the BMJ article, two other researchers questioned whether these claims had "solid or shaky foundations".
Martin McKee, a lecturer in European health organisation at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capwell, a lecturer in clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: "A fundamental principle of health is that rules should be based on evidence of effectiveness".
They said the public expects PHE's claims that "the current best estimate shows that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than tobacco smoking" to be based on a detailed analysis of evidence and modeling.
In fact, this is derived from a single meeting of 12 people who came together to develop a multi-criteria analysis model of decision making in order to summarize their views on the harm associated with various nicotine-containing products; the results of the meeting are summarized in a scientific publication.
McKee and Capewell reported that one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose CEO was reported to have previously received funding from British American Tobacco for independent research.
It also confirmed the BAT certificates in the health sector in the Sustainable Development Report.
One of the 12 people at the meeting announced funding from an e-cigarette manufacturer, without mentioning the funding he had reportedly received from tobacco company Philip Morris.
No reasonable explanation was provided for the board members' choice, but there are several prominent e-cigarette advocates among them, some of whom have also stated industry funding in publications.
It's not clear if the other participants in the meeting have any experience managing tobacco.
The meeting was also attended by the head of the tobacco sector at PHE.
The scientific paper published by the group "graciously agrees" that there is a lack of "substantial evidence of harmful effects of most products on most criteria", McKee and Capwell wrote.
However, none of these links and limitations were addressed in the PHE report.
McKee and Capwell said that PHE's claims that "there is no evidence at this time that e-cigarettes are a road leading children or non-smokers to smoking" are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, head of health and wellbeing at PHE, said the BMJ had previously responded to the claims.
He said: "E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than tobacco smoking".
One in two lifelong smokers died from their addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the health risks from e-cigarettes are relatively small, but we need to continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what is and is not proved by this evidence, especially where the public has had doubts about the relative hazard compared to tobacco.
About 80,000 people die each year from smoking-related diseases, and smoking costs the NHS £2 billion a year.
I've made it clear that while e-cigarettes are not safe, they do only a fraction of the damage that smoking does, we are doing our duty to the nation.
