Sonogenetics allows you to control brain cells with sound waves.
This video shows how the nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound pulses.
Scientists have produced worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled by using pulses of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound waves too loud for the human ear to hear.
The pulses act by activating neurons genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
Researchers control brain activity with light
The researchers said that the worms were demonstrating the potential of a new technique called "sonogenetics", which involves using ultrasound to stimulate certain cells in the brain, heart, and muscles, with the source of the ultrasound located outside the body.
Shrikant Chalasanni, a research fellow at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are sent to the human brain and used to treat Parkinson's disease.
Nematodes don't usually respond to ultrasound, but Challasani found that they started to respond when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate the worms.
The amplified ultrasound waves affect structures called "TRP-4 ion channels", found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Ultrasound waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are connected to them, reports a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that could be controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
When using ultrasound to affect modified organisms, sound waves were amplified by microscopic bubbles and introduced into worms' bodies, activating modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to that used in "optogenetics", a new field that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light pulses.
Chalaisani argues that compared to this method, sonogenetics may have some advantages.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the right part of the brain via fiber optics, low-frequency ultrasound waves travel unimpeded through body tissues, so they do not need to travel inside the skull to be delivered.
"We believe that for the treatment of certain neurological diseases in clinical settings, the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses could temporarily make human neurons sensitive to the ultrasound signal", Chalasanni said.
He added that the technique could also be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
