Kiev has broken the nuclear union.
Kiev formally refused Ukraine's cooperation with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnytsky NPP.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday voted for the dissolution of the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements on the completion of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but the project was never implemented.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine passed a law that cancels the agreement signed in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth blocks at the Khmelnytsky NPP.
The bill was only passed in the second round of voting, with 210 MPs supporting it, with the required minimum of 226, but then 234 MPs voted in favour of the bill in the second round.
The Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant, which was built during the Soviet Union, was originally designed to have four 1 GW power units with VVER type reactors, but only two were built.
Negotiations with Moscow on the completion led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement in 2010, in 2011-2012 the Rada adopted the relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the construction of blocks would have to be on credit of the Russian side, but funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling of relations between the two countries, Kiev began to cut ties with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing its refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant and the project to build a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only sphere where the relations were preserved, remained the purchase in Russia of fuel for the operating Ukrainian NPPs (provided about half of the production of electricity in the country), as for now the Ukrainian NPAEC "Energoat" can not replace the Russian supplies.
Plans to complete the construction of the Khmelnytsky NPP with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been abandoned: in 2014 in Kiev they announced negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS.
