FedEx's revenue is mixed, with a decline in 2016 forecasts.
FedEx reported disappointing results last quarter, and the shipping giant lowered its annual profit forecast due to falling demand for freight services and rising costs in its ground transportation division.
The company also said it plans to hire about 55,000 seasonal workers for the holidays.
At this time last year, FedEx announced that it would hire 50,000 temporary workers for the holidays.
Its shares fell about 2.5 percent in preliminary trading 45 minutes before the exchange opened on Wednesday.
FedEx Corp. said it plans to earn between $10.40 and $10.90 in the fiscal year ending next May, which is 20 cents less than the previous forecast.
Analysts were predicting $10.84 according to a FactSet review.
The forecast is down despite the 4.9 percent rate hike, which will take effect on January 4, and the increase in land charges for heavy or bulky goods, which begins in November.
The company said it still plans to increase revenue compared to last year due to cost reductions, higher gross revenue and growth in online commerce.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith stated that the company "operated steadily in light of weak, compared to forecast, economic conditions, especially in manufacturing and world trade".
The holiday hiring plans were announced the day after rival UPS announced that it planned to hire 95,000 more employees, about the same number it hired last year.
For the quarter ended August 31, FedEx earned $692 million, up 6 percent from a year earlier.
Earnings per share were $2.42, close to the average $2.44 per share forecast by Zacks Investment Research in a survey of 12 analysts.
Revenue increased by 5%, to $12.3 billion.
The six analysts interviewed by Zacks predicted $12.23 billion.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from a slump in the international express sector, which has led to a lack of growth in gross revenue in its express division.
However, the boom in online shopping has dramatically improved the results at the FedEx Ground.
In the last quarter, revenue from land transportation rose by 29%, but operating income remained largely unchanged due to higher expenses for large shipments and self-insurance.
The express division received higher income due to higher base rates, while the freight sector saw a decline in income due to higher labour costs.
At the preliminary auction about an hour before the opening, FedEx's stock fell $3.85, or 2.5 percent, to $150.15.
They closed Tuesday, down 11 percent year-over-year and 17 percent below the record set on June 11.
At the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve officials will spend two days this week at a 27-foot table made of Honduran redwood, deciding whether it's time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At one end of the richly decorated two-story meeting room, there will be a wall painting of the United States.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the nation's economic interests ahead of all others.
The central bank has received a dual mandate from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and to keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, the Federal government has recognized that there is a third unwritten mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate may be an unknown factor in the near-predicted decision to be announced on Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is ready to break away from the unprecedented stimulus provided by near-zero short-term interest rates since late 2008.
Even with most data showing solid growth, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may deter already cautious Federal officials from adding to the volatility by raising the federal funds base rate by even a quarter of a percentage point.
"It's clear that the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important considerations", said Lindsay M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I think that if they were looking for a reason not to raise the stakes, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough to give them an excuse to wait any longer", she noted.
There's no consensus on what they're going to do at the Federal Reserve, which in itself is causing the financial market to fluctuate.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted a higher interest rate this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Federal Reserve to refrain from doing so, with a key indicator showing only about a 30 percent chance of a rapid upturn.
It could lead to a stock market crash if the Federal Reserve raises the rate, provided that those making the decisions don't soften the blow by promising that the next rise won't be anytime soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The jump was triggered by expectations that the Federal Reserve's policymakers would leave the bet this week, said John Lonsky, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research.
"It would be a surprise if the Federal system raises rates at this point in time", he noted.
If the Federal Reserve Board does this, "they will have to go a long way in establishing their strategy to keep the financial markets in check so they don't panic".
Other experts objected that the rate hike could calm the financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Federal System would operate.
Just a month ago, the federal system seemed inclined to raise the rate by 0.25 percent this month, making the first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labor market growth has been stable this year.
Unemployment dropped to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest in more than seven years, and near what the federal system considers full employment.
Wage growth is showing signs of acceleration.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank's target of 2 percent annually, the Federal Reserve said the key cause was the temporary effect of the sharp drop in oil prices.
The economy "can and needs to cope with higher rates, given the shrinking labor market", observed Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much as 16% from a record high in May as investors feared a slowdown in China could dampen global growth.
The market has partially recovered this month, and the Dow Jones is now about 10% below its May high.
For the Federal Reserve, the market upset further complicates the difficult calculations of the interest rate hikes.
"Without the information on what's happened in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, they would have been twisting the nuts at this meeting", said Steven D. Oliner, a senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the Federal Reserve System.
Now, he predicts, they'll wait at least a month to get more control over the consequences.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about what the impact on the U.S. economy might be, and they have almost no reliable data after the recent events in China", Ohliner said.
The health of the global economy is not a top concern of the Federal System, and technically it should not be considered in these decisions.
But in essence, the Federal Reserve has become the world's financial power.
The Central Bank's influence in recent years has been enormous.
A single hint from then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve could "mute" its monetary expansion caused markets around the world to shake.
In a world where markets and economic systems are increasingly intertwined, one would expect that the heads of the Federal Reserve System would not only monitor developments everywhere, but also consult with representatives of other central banks and experts to better understand the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science", said Zachary Carabell, head of Envestnet Inc., a company that deals with global wealth management strategies.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that "there have been instances in the history of the Federal Reserve System of overreaction to financial market movements that seem to be unrelated to economic principles".
Laker, a voting member of the influential Federal Open Market Committee who insisted on raising rates, cited the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its base rate by 0.75% in three sessions, "despite limited identifiable implications for growth in the U.S"., Lacker said.
A year later, the Federal System's executives repealed the cuts.
The Federal Reserve should only prioritize stability concerns during major crises, such as the 2008 market crash", said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate-setting committee.
The last panic didn't come close to that level, he said.
"You wouldn't want to be in a situation where you're scared of rising rates because the markets are in a state of shock", said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for World Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and doesn't mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should be ahead of the curve.
