Obesity surgery can help diabetics who are slightly obese
The beneficial effects of obesity surgery on people with mild obesity and type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to say that people with mild obesity live longer after obesity surgery than those who do not receive surgery.
"The death toll is not coming out right away", said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert on obesity surgery, who wrote about the new study in a column for JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses various techniques to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the ability of organisms to digest food.
In a few years, bariatric surgery has proven its effectiveness in treating type 2 diabetes, but the main research has been done on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, the measure of weight relative to height, is considered normal if it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI of over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at the Taiwanese Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and arm gastrectomy - with medical treatment for type 2 diabetes in people with moderate obesity.
The average BMI of surgeons dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains at about 29.
Of those who had surgery, 36% were completely cured of diabetes, and 28% were partially cured.
In the medicated group, for comparison, only about 1 percent of the patients were completely cured of diabetes, and only about 2 percent were partially cured.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgical group", the authors state.
The researchers also monitored the levels of hemoglobin A1c in the blood, which reflects blood sugar levels in the dynamics.
It is better to keep hemoglobin A1c below 7 percent, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
In the treatment group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
But better glycemic control, reflected in good hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over five years, said study leader Dr. Chi-Cheng Su and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes of two types of surgery.
By the fifth year, compared with the group that had completed a sleeve gastrectomy, the shunt group lost more weight (18.7 kg versus 14.2 kg), achieved a greater decrease in BMI (by 7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%), and was also closer to complete diabetes remission (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not show any benefit of surgery in terms of life expectancy after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgery does lead to an increase in life expectancy, reports Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine in Phoenix.
A Swedish study found that for obese people who chose bariatric intervention, the odds of dying within 15 years were about 29 percent lower than for the more traditional treatment group.
Although the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that it encourages people with BMI under 35 to be interested in the procedure.
"The report is very important here because it says that this surgery is safe in the low BMI group, where there is no increased risk of death or kidney disease", she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously once a patient's BMI falls between 27 and 30.
"I think we've been waiting too long to get people to take this seriously", she said.
I think once they've accumulated the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it's very difficult to reverse it.
