The number of children who have swallowed hand sanitizer has quadrupled in the last four years.
Toxicology centers in the United States have reported a nearly 400-percent increase since 2010 in children under 12 years of age who ingest hand sanitizer with high alcohol content, according to the Georgia Toxicology Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Toxicology Center, the number of children under 12 years of age who swallowed hand sanitizer fluids reported to the toxicology center increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children are exposed to these substances more often, and unfortunately, a certain percentage of them are sent to the emergency room", Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children drink disinfectant liquids on purpose, and some do it to impress their friends or to argue for social media.
Videos on YouTube show teenagers drinking disinfectant liquid as a cheap beverage.
The teenagers reportedly mixed the disinfectant with an alcohol-containing mouthwash to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the pleasant smell of disinfectant fluid.
"The child doesn't think it can hurt him", Lopez said.
Many of the most attractive (hand sanitizers) are those that are flavored.
There are hand sanitizers with the scent of strawberries, grapes, oranges, which are very appealing to children.
Hand sanitizer fluid contains somewhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
In young children, especially, just a few sprays can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's high-concentration alcohol", said Dr. Stephen Thornton, chief of the toxicology center at the University of Kansas Hospital, to Fox 4 in Kansas City.
You wouldn't just leave a whiskey bottle, but people keep these hand sanitizers in mind, and if kids get to them, it's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Naija Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently swallowed about four sprays of strawberry-flavored hand sanitizer at school, was sent to the emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol level was 179, twice that of an adult who is legally considered to be intoxicated, according to Dr. Chris Ritchie, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center near Atlanta.
Naija was speechless and unable to walk when she was taken to the emergency room.
Doctors watched her all night in a separate children's clinic to avoid missing any signs of brain injury, as the girl fell and hit her head from alcohol, Ritchie said.
"It was very scary", said Orthoria Scott, Naiji's mother, to CNN.
It could have been fatal to my baby.
Lopez recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic substances or disinfectant wipes, in addition to keeping hand-disinfectant liquids out of children's reach.
Besides alcohol poisoning, some disinfectant fluids have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after ingesting a disinfectant containing a toxic unidentified ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, a deadly agent, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as the active substance.
In January, three fourth-graders in upstate New York conspired to poison their "opposing" teacher by "spreading antibacterial substances in the classroom", according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand sanitizers, and she has banned them from her classroom.
Police believe the failed plan was "bullshit talk", and are directing disciplinary action to the school district.
