The economy is a global issue.
The processes of globalization were supposed to reduce inequality in the world.
The reality is that the income gap in the developing economies is growing.
Eric Maskin. What are you doing?
To correct this, it is necessary to raise the level of education of low-skilled workers, says Eric Maskin, chief research officer of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of Decisions at the Higher Education University of the Czech Republic, and 2007 Nobel Prize winner in economics.
In the last twenty years, the world has experienced an unprecedented growth of global markets.
Trade between the countries was becoming more and more open.
The proponents of globalization predicted great benefits for the developing economies.
"And these predictions have largely come true", Maskin points out.
China and India, for example, have seen significant growth in GDP per capita.
But it's not all that good.
Globalization was expected to reduce the gap between the rich and the poor in poor countries, which is reflected in the great inequality of income, or more precisely, in wages.
But in fact, inequality has only increased, notes Eric Maskin in his article "Why Global Markets Have Failed to Reduce Inequality in Emerging Economies", published in The World Bank Economic Review, translated and quoted by the HSE.
Eric Maskin, in collaboration with Harvard University economist Michael Kremer, has developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why income gaps in poor countries are widening as globalization increases, according to the HSE Research Institute.
Specific processes are taking place in the new global market.
To demonstrate this, Maskin sets out four levels of expertise -- A and B for rich countries, C and D for poor countries.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries lack the level of skills to cooperate with A and B specialists from rich countries.
And if the C-level workers in poor countries are getting higher because of cooperation with B-level workers in rich countries, then the D-level workers are either not getting any more or their wages are falling.
The bottom line is that internationalization of production will increase the wage gap between the two categories of workers in poor countries and, consequently, increase the level of inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskin propose a surprisingly beautiful model, an alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantage.
It explains why globalization has led to income inequality", says Fuad Aleskerov, associate professor, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Making, head of the mathematics department at HSE.
And like any powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this area.
The solution, according to Eric Maskin, is to raise the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the researchers note that the workers themselves do not have the means to do so, and the companies do not have the means to pay for their training.
Governments, international agencies, NGOs and private foundations can play a significant role in this situation, Maskin believes.
The scientist notes that the theory developed does not call for stopping the process of globalization, which has brought and is bringing its fruits in the form of the growth of the GDP of countries.
