Derbent, one of Russia's oldest cities, is celebrating its 2000th anniversary this September.
The program of the festivities includes the festival of national cultures of the peoples of Dagestan and a fair in the style of the past, the exhibition of derbent carpets and the Open Churches Day, the historical-musical show "2000 years in two hours" and excursions to the reconstructed museum of Peter I.
The medieval stones of the fortress of Naryn-Kala, the ancient Arabic inscriptions on the walls, the narrow streets and palace gardens - all of this is as if taken from the pages of "A Thousand and One Nights".
Derbent is the only city in Russia that has been preserved in its place since ancient times.
Although it was claimed by the Roman Empire, Byzantium, the Khazar Khanate and the Golden Horde.
The age of the eastern plantain trees growing in the courtyard of the Derbent Jama-mosque is several centuries.
These powerful plants are protected by the All-Russian program "Trees - Monuments of Living Nature".
The shade of the sprawling crowns saves pilgrims and tourists during the summer heat.
Visitors to the mosque will be served with aromatic tea and will be served with Dagestan delicacies - honey fig, hummus, mushroom, miracle cakes, ayran and sweets.
In Derbent, large samovars have been used for centuries to make tea for many guests at once.
The inscription above the entrance to the Jumma mosque says that the building was built in the year 115 Hijri.
That's 733 in the Gregorian calendar.
It is the oldest mosque in Russia.
The interior is impressive in scale and solemnity: the arcades of the domes and vaults are supported by square columns and illuminated by the sun's rays from tiny windows.
The keeping and breeding of pigeons is a traditional pastime of the people of Derbent.
The owners of domestic birds put pigeonholes in their yards, under trees, in attics.
The thrilling sight is the flight of a flock of white doves, which resemble the flashes of a festive firework.
In order to protect themselves from the enemy, the ancient Persians built a double stone wall around the Caspian Gate.
Going 500 meters into the sea, this structure closed the harbor of Derbent.
In 2003, the fortress walls of Derbent were included in the UNESCO World Heritage List as the best preserved monument of ancient Persian fortification architecture.
Carpets were woven in Derbent as early as the fifth century C.E., and the technology of this unique craft has remained almost unchanged to this day.
On one of the streets adjacent to the city market, carpets are sold for all tastes - strips of wool, cotton, or silk of all colors and shades, with or without a warp, with intricate ornamentation and a fanciful rim.
The city was built from the beginnings of the maghals, one-story stone buildings.
The maggots have hardly changed in years.
Just the satellite dishes, air conditioning on the walls and street lights remind you that you are not in a medieval city, but in a modern one.
In the old part of the city, details of a water pipe built by the Persians about a thousand years ago have been preserved.
The ancient springs, from which the local people still draw water, have survived to the present day.
Many Derbent people prefer water from historic wells to ordinary tap water.
Derbent was one of the centers of pottery.
Watered and painted vases, dishes, pots, and cups were valued throughout the Caucasus.
Potters still make wonderful ceramic objects for practical and souvenir use.
On holidays and festivals, crowds of spectators gather under a stretched rope, on which the pupils of the Republican School of Circus Art perform.
The history of this amazing and risky craft goes back several centuries.
The new trend is that we're seeing more and more girls in the rope-walking community.
In the premises of the former Virgin Bath, the Museum of Culture and Life of the Ancient Derbent is now open.
In the past, unmarried girls and brides were accompanied by their friends to bathe here, but now anyone can see the vaulted-dome hall, hot and cold pools, which are gone into the past with the bathing equipment.
Most homes in Derbent have hot water, but baths and steam rooms are as popular today as they were in the old days.
The benefits of steam heating are written in ancient books.
After bathing, blood flow improves, muscles lose fatigue, and the body becomes more flexible and light.
The festival "Sodruzhstvo", which takes place in the territory of the fortress of Naryn-Kala, is attended by ethno-housemates from many districts of Dagestan.
The participants in national costumes dance, play folk tunes, sing the songs of the Caucasus peoples and treat the visitors to delicious homemade cheese.
Kirkhlar is the burial place of forty martyrs who laid down their heads for Islam.
It is one of the most revered complexes for Muslims of the North Caucasus.
The yellowing sarcophagi are carved from solid stone blocks and oriented, as is customary among Arabs, along the west-east axis.
Brothers Gavril and Albert Yakubows cut and shave customers in a small salon near the Upper Bazaar.
The barber shop has been here for years.
The techniques of the craftsman's crafts are passed down from generation to generation.
The Yakubov brothers can do not only traditional, but also the most modern hairstyle.
On one of the streets of the Old City, a house in which the exiled writer-Decembrist Alexander Bestuzhev-Marlinsky lived has been preserved.
After learning the Turkic language and collecting ethnographic material, he described the Derbent of the first third of the XIX century with its ancient monuments, life and life of the city's inhabitants.
The teahouse is a traditional Eastern club, serving only tea and homemade pastries.
Men come here to quench their thirst, to talk to their friends, to solve some work problems.
As in the old days, women are not allowed to cross the teahouse threshold.
Derbent dance ensemble "Caspian" was created three years ago, but has already had time to take part in events of the republican and Russian level.
The ensemble's soloists rehearse every day, perfecting the folk dances of the Avars, the Dargas, the Tatars, and the Armenians.
As the evening approaches, when the noise subsides and street lamps are lit, locals sit at stalls near houses with protruding terraces.
Usually, the Derbent discusses the issues of the day.
But on the eve of the anniversary, they are increasingly recalling episodes of their city's unique history that influenced the fate of the entire Black Sea-Caspian region.
