The Green Tribunal was quick to execute.
A typical situation: four officials stand at the desk of Judge Swatantar Kumar, listening to his complaints about the work done.
The court is not at all satisfied with the quality of your work.
"We didn't give you a 110-page order to make fun of", says Kumar.
If one more brick is laid, we'll order all existing buildings to be demolished.
Kumar heads the National Green Tribunal (NGT), a judicial body set up in 2010 to stop the rapid environmental pollution that has accompanied the economic boom of recent decades.
During this time, the Tribunal has handled more than 10,000 lawsuits related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological development, toxic waste, and dam construction.
In two out of three cases, the court decides to stop construction that leads to pollution.
The stakes are incredibly high: in less than 60 years since independence, India has gone from a jungle country to one of the most overpopulated and polluted countries in the world.
The problem is particularly acute in large cities, where infrastructure development is not catching up with rapid urbanization: cities are covered in dense smog, rivers are filled with pesticides and waste from businesses and households, and the few remaining residential areas are being cut down for new housing developments.
Despite the formal support of the green movement from the state, the NZT is regularly criticized by the Narendra Modi government as it often becomes the main reason for cancellation of major investment projects.
In May, the environment minister called the court's decisions "extreme" and "unenforceable".
Sometimes it is impossible to execute court decisions within the time limit set by the court, environmental lawyer Raj Panjwani confirms.
But there's a positive side to unreachable deadlines: At least they get the responsible people moving.
"His main goal is to shake up the system", the lawyer adds.
The Green Tribunal has repeatedly cancelled major construction projects: it has stopped the construction of an airport, a power station and hundreds of smaller buildings.
People are also being considered, for example, when discussing the fate of a drug company in Telangana state that contaminated a local river with fluoride.
We can close your factory, but we're responsible for the economic consequences.
"People will lose their jobs", Kumar commented on his decision.
However, such explanations are far from always understandable to ordinary people, whose lives can be changed by a single stroke of the judge's pen.
In April, the Tribunal decided to ban all vehicles over 10 years old from entering the capital, which caused a public outcry.
Despite the sharp drop in popularity and the barrage of criticism, Swatantar Kumar refused to overturn this decision.
Instead, he ordered statistics on incoming and outgoing vehicles from the Delhi government, and also proposed purchasing 10,000 additional buses, having previously checked with the factories to see if they were able to fulfill the order.
As the courts began to focus on sources of pollution such as landfills, fuel quality, and even traffic accidents, the public's anger began to ease.
But the most sickening topic of the judge's ruling was the cleanup of the Ganges, announced with great pomp by Prime Minister Narendra Modi last year.
When it comes to the Ganges, a sacred river for Hindus, the judge often loses his temper and starts screaming.
Do you know what the word "saint" means?
Someone poured water from the Ganges on the statue of God, and it turned out to be feces, the judge warms up.
You keep polluting the river because you think, "The Ganges is the Ganges, it will take away all our sins".
This is the river we worship, and look what you do to it every day.
The clean-up of the Ganges is the most ambitious and costly environmental project announced by the new government.
Currently, the number of fecal bacteria in this river is more than 120 times the norm.
Each year, between 1.5 and 3 of the 700 million Hindus who bathe there die from infectious diseases.
In February, Narendra Modi even donated the proceeds from the sale of his suit, in which he met Barack Obama, and 455 other items from his personal collection to the Ganga Rescue Fund.
Environmentalists immediately accused the prime minister of populism: the suit was bought for 700 thousand dollars, while the river cleaning requires at least eight billion.
Green Tribunal supporters agree that India has a long way to go before it can call itself a developed country, but they do not believe that progress should be at the expense of the environment.
"In a developing country, talking about the environment is often viewed as an unconscionable luxury", says Call of the Gang activist Malik Bhanot.
And the court is trying to find a middle ground between ecology and development".
